      <hedline>
        <hl1>Are School Vouchers the Answer?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Stephen J Plank says many factors must be examined before decision is made to divert public funds to private schools, not just the higher test scores among black students on scholarships at private schools (Aug 30 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Higher test scores among black students on scholarships at private schools (news article, Aug. 30) may not be because the schools are private but because of smaller class size, greater discipline, higher expectations and greater parental involvement.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Higher test scores among black students on scholarships at private schools (news article, Aug. 30) may not be because the schools are private but because of smaller class size, greater discipline, higher expectations and greater parental involvement.</p>
        <p>These factors must be examined before a decision is made to divert public funds to private institutions instead of using the funds to help our public schools achieve the same standards.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN J. PLANK  San Rafael, Calif., Aug. 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
